All files can be printed without support. Photos shown were printed on a Replicator 2 and sliced using the standard setting on Makerware.

description.text:
I liked https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2113975 but wanted to use a Lisiparoi LED ring to shed some light on my prints. So I redesigned the camera case. You can use it directly on thing 2113975 or you can remove the three arms and connect you own adapter. Print with 0.2mm layer height is possible.

UPDATE: In certain settings the space for the connector to the Lisiparoi proved to be a little too small. Together with vibrations during a print, the back would fall off. In V2 the space for the connector is a bit larger. The back has a higher rim to make more contact with the front. After two tweeks of testing this version, it didn't fall off. Yet :)

FREE BONUS! :) I've added a cable clip to keep the camera and Lisiparoi cable together. Before use, first bend the clip along the two thin parts. Squeeze the bends, with your fingers, hard. Insert the Lisiparoi cable, followed by the camera cable. Bend over the part with the hole, then the part with the cylinder. Finally, push the cylinder in the hole and squeeze it tight. Layer height 0.1mm advised.

The Lisiparoi also comes in an infrared design for use with the Raspberry Pi NOIR camera. The infrared LED's will become hotter than the visible ones, but after a few hours the case doesn't get hotter than 40-50 °C so that seems OK. More information about the Lisiparoi here: http://www.lisiparoi.com.

In case you want to design your own case for the Lisiparoi, you can use my model as a designing aid: https://grabcad.com/library/lisiparoi-v1-0-1.

A remix of Steamkraft's Wanhao Duplicator I3 Y-Plate.

Changes made:

  • Added a 3-point leveling location to the side since a front/back location doesn't quite work (the screw would either hit the Y stepper motor or the front plate- you'll need to rotate the build plate 90 degrees and extend the wires for 3-point leveling). I left the original hole for a potential cable chain mount.
  • Added extra bearing and belt bracket mount holes. This allows use of 3 bearings or 4 bearings, and to orient the 3 point leveling location to either side.
  • Expanded the leveling screw holes by 0.1mm

I had my plate cut in 3mm carbon fiber, but this could also be milled in aluminum.

Added a v2 that has slots on the rear center tab. The idea being to use a zip tie to hold the heated build plate wires to relieve any stress on the solder points under the bed. This was something I didn't think about until I was installing the one I had made, so it is untested.

title: Multi-Color Pride Flag (use any printer by swapping filaments)

description.text:
June is Pride month.

As a company, we typically try to avoid taking stances on anything that could be deemed political. But we believe that equality, diversity, and equal rights for all are things worth fighting for and celebrating.

So—we'll brandish this flag proudly, with several of us joining in at Pride Toronto (where we call home).

(Any printer can print this Pride Flag! See instructions below.)

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

Any / 30%

Notes:

This pride flag was printed at 60mm high (with 0.2mm layer heights, that's 300 layers).

The flag has 6 even bands of color (with 300 layers, that's about 50 layers per color). But since the top of the flag is a bit wavy, we swapped colors every 49 layers so the red band wasn't too small.

So, we swapped filaments at layers: 49, 98, 147, 196, 245.

We did this by slicing the g-code file and searching for "layer 49", "layer 98", and so on in the G-code file. Then, we manually added beep and pause commands to tell us when to swap filaments.

For this print, we used a CraftBot that can accept G197 commands (pause print and move head to home position, and wait for instructions to resume print). We inserted the following code:

M300 ; play beep sound
G197 ; pause print, move to home position, wait for instructions

This allowed us not to have to watch the print too carefully. Then, every time the printer beeped (at layers 49, 98, 147, ...) we manually unloaded/loaded filament to swap colors, and resumed the print until the next pause.

For printers that do not accept G197 commands, you could do the following:
M300 ; play beep sound
G4 P4000 ; pause print for 4 seconds

So long as you hear your printer beep, the 4 seconds should be enough for you to know when to change your filament. (Some printers do not respond to pause commands that are longer than 5 seconds.)

This print took about 3 hrs 30 min at a print speed of 40mm/s.

title: Zhiyun Smooth-Q Pool Pole Support
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I wanted to mount my Zhiyun Smooth-Q gimbal to a pole for aerial shots but, though the gimbal has a tripod mount at the bottom of the handle, I didn't like the whole gimbal to be held that way in all sorts of positions (horizontal to vertical).

I also wanted to have the longest adjustable pole available for a modest price. I thought about using an extra aluminum pool cleaning pole I had on hands.

I therefore designed this support which holds the gimbal both by the bottom 1/4"-20 mount as well as the top of the handle making for a very secure mounting with adjustable angle.

The clamp is a very customized version of this design: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1012573

The knobs for the 1/4" bolts and nuts are taken from here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2267262 while the knobs for the M3 clamp bolt and nut can be found here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2383326

If you want to add a plug at the end of the inner aluminum tube (if you use it alone to keep the end from digging into the ground), you can print and use the following: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2390255

See below for printing instructions, bill of material and assembly instructions.

Printer:

Printrbot Simple Metal

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.3mm

Infill:

20%

Notes:

In order to print the parts individually, you can separate the mesh parts in your slicer.

The two parts of the clamp are printed at once and if your printer is well tuned, they will easily separate after printing. If you need to adjust adhesion between the two parts of the clamp, you can tweak your extrusion rate or, if you use Simplify3D, you can use the "Horizontal size compensation" to that effect.

You may want to enable support for the pole mount (hole for the nut that prints underneath the part).

For a complete support, you'll need to print the following:
1X pole mount
1X gimbal support bracket
1X gimbal clamp (all three parts are plated in the included STL)
4X 1/4"-20 bolt knobs
2X M3 knobs

Bill of Material:

You'll need the following fasteners in order to assemble the support:
1X 1/4"-20 by 1 3/4" long bolt and one 1/4"-20 dome nut to affix the pole mount to aluminum pole
1X 1/4"-20 by 1 1/2" long bolt, one 6mm washer and one 1/4"-20 dome nut for the pole mount to gimbal support bracket swivel assembly
1X 1/4"-20 by 1" long bolt and a 6mm washer for the tripod mount of the gimbal
1X M3 20mm long bolt, two washers and one nylock nut for the clamp hinge
1X M3 20mm long bolt and 2 nuts that need to be glued into the small knobs used to close the clamp
1X M3 20mm long bolt as well as 1X M3 8mm long bolt and nut to mount the clamp to the support bracket.

You'll also need some 1/8" thick by 1/4" wide closed-cell adhesive foam strip to pad the contact points between the gimbal and the support.

Assembly Instructions:

Normally, you attach the broom or net to a pool pole on the bigger section and once extended, you handle it by the smallest section. But given we are going to be wielding the extended pole up in the air, it is much more efficient to mount our support to the smaller of the two rods and keep the larger one close to the ground. For this, you'll need to first modify your pole by removing the handle cap on the smaller of the two rods (27mm ID one) and drill a 1/4" hole for the mounting bolt 30mm from the end.

Then, we'll assemble the pole mount: First press the 1/4" dome nut and the 1 3/4" bolt into two of the four large knobs. Then press the second 1/4" dome nut into the hex recess in the pole mount. To assemble on the pole, insert the pole mount into the pole and align the holes so that you can insert and thread together the knobs with bolt and dome nut.

We'll now assemble the pivot hinge of the clamp by inserting the M3 by 20mm long bolt through the hinge with washers on each side and nylock nut at the end of the bolt.

You can now attach the clamp onto the gimbal support bracket by securing it with an M3 by 20mm bolt in the blind hole and an M3 by 8mm bolt and nut (the nut goes into the hexagonal recess in the support bracket). Ensure you put the sharp recess in the clamp towards the outside of the support bracket so as to marry with the profile of the Smooth-Q gimbal's handle. You can now cover with halves of the clamp with some adhesive foam strips as shown in the picture. Prepare both small knobs by threading completely and tightening one nut on the M3 by 20mm bolt, pushing it through one handle and securing with epoxy glue. For the second small knob, just insert a nut into it and secure with epoxy glue. Both small knobs can now be inserted into the clamp end end threaded together and left so the glue cures.

We'll prepare the tripod support end by puting small pieces of foam adhesive where it will contact the gimble and assemble the knob by pressing into one of the two large knob left the 1/4" by 1" bolt, inserting the 6mm washer on the bolt in between the knob and the support bracket.

Take the last large knob and press in the 1/4" by 1 1/2" long bolt, inserting a 6mm washer at the end of the bolt. Last we'll secure support bracket to the pole mount by threading the knob we just made through the two halves of the swivel joint of the bracket and mount (which has a dome nut into it's hex recess).

You can now mount your gimbal to the support by threading the knob with 1" bolt at the bottom of the handle and close and secure the clamp ensuring you rotate the gimbal's handle so the the control panel is on the outside of the bracket (so that it matches with the square recess in the clamp).

Enjoy your aerial shots!

This thing was made with Tinkercad. Edit it online https://www.tinkercad.com/things/67ejveLb0sP

Design requirements were:

  • No need to modify the gimbal
  • Keep the gimbal fully functional (including control panel)
  • Allow the gimbal to be positioned at different angles
  • Parts should print without need for support

title: Maker Select Plus / Wanhao Duplicator i3 Plus Hotend PCB Mount

description.text:
For the Monoprice Maker Select Plus and Wanhao Duplicator i3 Plus:

This mount is used to relocate the PCB for all the hotend components out of the way to free up the carriage block for mounting alternate fan coolers. This retains all stock hardware.

*VERY IMPORTANT** You will need to verify that the heads of the countersunk screws used to attach the bracket to the printer are screwed in completely and that the PCB does not come into contact with these screws when mounted. If any of the PCB leads on the underside of the board touch the screws, you could have an electrical short to your board and cause some serious damage. I believe I have modeled this with plenty of clearance; however, I can only reference the board on my machine and yours may have slightly longer leads.

• Remove the PCB cover, then remove the PCB bracket from the carriage block (reuse fasteners in next step). Finally, remove the PCB itself from the bracket (reuse fasteners in final step).

  • Using the countersunk screws, attach the new bracket to the top two threads of the lower carriage block.

  • Using the screws and washers removed from the PCB mount, reattach the PCB in it's new orientation.

*****Please note that the screws holding the PCB to the bracket should self-tap into the new bracket, but can be stripped if you tighten them too much. This is designed this way to help prevent anyone from tightening these screws too much and damaging their PCB.

This thing allows mounting http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:87250 Case for the Full Graphic Smart LCD Controller by wersy to the left front corner of the AM8 Full Metal Frame for the Anet A8 printer. Additional Items:

1 x m6 x 35mm screw
1 x m6 nylon lock nut
3 x m6 flat washers
2 x m5 x 10mm button head screws
1 x m5 square nut
2 x m3 x 10mm screws
2x m3 hex nuts

Installation:

If you are adding this to an already completed AM8 frame you will need to remove the front cross piece to allow installation of 1 m5 square nut in the lower channel on the left side of the left frame piece. You will need to thread the lower hole in the extrusion with an m5 tap as you did for the uprights. Install the m5 nylon lock nut in the hexagon recess on the new corner bracket. Replace the printed corner bracket with the new one

Now for the LCD Display mount place 2 m6 flat washers on the m6 x 35mm screw, slide it through the 6mm hole on the LCD Display Mount with the washers and head of the screw in the recess. Place the last m6 flat washer on the screw and attached the LCD Display Mount to the corner bracket. Tighten the screw to provide enough tension on the LCD Display mount to hold it in place.

Install your RAMPS smart controller in the case following the instructions provided by wersy. You can now mount the display case to the LCD Display mount.

Many thanks to harryarnold for his 2020 LCD Display Mount Design and to wersy for his Case for the Full Graphic Smart LCD Controller design. Both are very well done and easy to print.

title: An adjustable hologram box generator for screens

description.text:
Do you have LCD screens you no longer need? Here is a project that will allow you to recycle them.

The hologram technology used is based on an optical effect called Pepper's ghost: the reflection of a screen in a glass creates the illusion, looking at the glass, that the object is behind. For this project, I place a screen suspended over a transparent pyramid giving a body to the reflections of a screen not visible to the viewer.

This box generator is designed for screens ranging from the smallest tablets to the largest PC monitors. The box was considered on a square base, designating the slabs in 4/3 format as the most suitable, without limitation for the 16 / 9th. The generator provides a vector file for a laser cutter, which is commonly found in a fablab.

The box can be made in medium or plywood. The support columns between the lower box and the case of the screen can be made of transparent acrylic (Plexiglas) so as not to interfere with vision.

I have not yet found a product reference for the material of the pyramid. At first, I used acrylic coated with solar film tinted for car window, without result. I then used a pyramid purchased in a tablet kit, the result is perfect. I still can not find equivalent material on the market to cut a pyramid using the generator, to the dimensions of my screen. Any help in the comments would be very appreciated!

Because I use a french version of the GPL, I cannot upload my files on Thingiverse (only 2d_sony.scad.svg as example). The project is fully open source and can be downloaded here https://gitlab.com/influencepc/generateur-de-boite-a-hologramme/repository/archive.zip?ref=master

I'm sorry to have only published the project in french here https://gitlab.com/influencepc/generateur-de-boite-a-hologramme

title: Laser collimation kit - Collimator for newtonian telescope

description.text:
English version

Introduction

Here's my version of the laser collimator for Newtonian telescope. It allows fast and pretty accurate mirrors alignment. It comes with its own calibration stand, to ensure that the collimator is in fact collimated ... What's more, I added a very convenient (and simple) rotary switch to keep the laser on)

What you need

  • The three printed parts
  • A cheap green laser pen like this one (others could work the same)
  • 6 x M3 screws (I use 16mm, I think 12/13mm is great)

Cost : less than 5€ .. Not bad ;)

How to use it

  1. Insert the screws in the six holes. The laser pen should be able to move but keep centered.
  2. Install the switch as shown on the picture above.
  3. Secure the pen with the first three screws. (in the middle of the body) Check if the laser beam go well through the hole. If not, it's not well-centered.
  4. Place the collimator onto the calibration stand and switch on the laser.
  5. The stand has to be strongly secured on a stable surface, and the beam should hit a 10m far wall (the further the better). Spin the collimator, keeping it right in the V stand. The laser should make kind of a circle on the wall. With the three other screws, try to align correctly the pen to make this circle tiniest as possible.
  6. Congratulation ! You can use it now as any other laser collimator. Internet is full of marvelous tutorials .. ;)

Keep it mind that laser collimators help a lot to collimate a telescope, but it is very useful to enhance it with a star and the Airy disk ...

Version française

Présentation

Sur Thingiverse, les collimateurs laser c'est comme les recettes de gâteaux, chacun a la sienne. Voici ma version pour les télescopes Newton. Il permet un alignement des miroirs rapide et assez précis. Je le publie avec son propre support de calibration, pour s'assurer que le collimateur est lui-même collimaté ... J'ai aussi dessiné un bouton rotatif très simple qui permet de garder le laser allumé.

Ce dont vous aurez besoin

  • Les trois parties imprimées
  • Un stylo-laser vert chinois (d'autres modèles doivent être compatibles aussi)
  • 6 vis M3 (J'utilise des 16mm, car c'est ce que j'ai. Prévoir au moins 12/13mm)

Prix : moins de 5€ ... Pas mal ;)

Mode d'emploi

  1. Insérer les vis dans les six trous prévus à cet effet. Le laser doit pouvoir coulisser mais aussi être maintenu au centre.
  2. Mettre en place le bouton comme montré sur la photo.
  3. Serrer le laser avec les trois vis du centre. Vérifier que le faisceau laser passe bien dans le trou. Sinon c'est qu'il n'est pas bien centré.
  4. Placer le collimateur sur son support de calibration.
  5. Le support doit être solidement fixé à une surface stable, et le laser doit taper dans un mur à environ 10m. (le plus loin sera le mieux) Tourner le collimateur en le gardant bien dans son socle. Le laser devrait dessiner un rond sur le mur. Avec les trois autres vis, orienter le laser pour essayer de rendre le rond le plus petit possible (l'idéal serait un point fixe)
  6. Bravo ! Il peut maintenant être utilisé comme n'importe quel collimateur laser, internet regorge de tutoriels merveilleux ;)

Le collimateur laser permet de dégrossir beaucoup le travail, et ce rapidement. Mais n'oubliez pas que la meilleure collimation possible sera obtenue en affinant le travail avec une étoile et son disque d'Airy.

description.text: This is a replacement part for Velux latch. just unscrew the metal part, remove the broken latch and insert this new one.

Derived from another KR180 model I found online, with holes fixed for better slicing.
I thought I uploaded these files in December 2012. Something must have happened to them :O

See also https://www.marginallyclever.com/2012/12/kuka-kr180-from-thingiverse-fixed/

Made this for my good lady to keep her oils together because they were doing my head in lying around everywhere.......You can use it for anything that'll fit into the +/- 26mm diameter holes (6 per tier = 12 in total per stand or 24 if you double it up).

I may make one for humbrol model paints too (just need to make holes bigger)

I have included the sketch up model to allow you to make your own changes too. There are two types of base, male and female.It doesn't matter what you print unless you are looking to connect another stand 'back to back'. You will need to glue this together epoxy is the ultimate but superglue or plumbers waste-pipe glue (especially with abs) also work very well.

Print any way you want, the model is forgiving so I'd just go with fast and default settings. You'll get good results whatever you do.

When using ABS I like Polypipe SC250 solvent cement, it fuses your surfaces together and nearly makes it one solid piece (careful though it kinda melts plastics so go easy!)
